references: We first report the results on the CrowdPose dataset [26]. Compared to Microsoft COCO [28], it contains more crowded scenes. The strong assumption of top-down methods that each person detection box only contains a single person in the center is hard to satisfy in crowded scenes. Therefore, several top-down methods [15, 10] that perform well on the COCO dataset [28] fail on the CrowdPose dataset [26]. We also achieve a much better performance-computation trade-off than the state-of-the-art bottom-up HRNet-based baselines [8, 36]. As shown in Table 1 and Figure 9, our architecture achieves 2.8×2.8\times MACs reduction and up to 5.0×5.0\times latency reduction on mobile platforms compared with HRNet-based methods.

references: We also show the results on Microsoft COCO dataset [28]. Our method outperforms HRNet-based approaches [8, 36] by a large margin. As shown in Table 2 and Figure 1, our architecture achieves up to 2.4×2.4\times with even higher performance. Besides, compared with Lightweight Openpose [39], our method performs much better (+14.014.0+14.0AP) with lower latency on mobile platforms.

Knl.: Kernel size; Fsn: Fusion deconv head; Spnt.: Supernet training; Dstl: Distillation. Large kernels and the fusion deconv head provide +13.013.0+13.0AP and +7.67.6+7.6AP, respectively. The supernet training benefits both two configurations by up to +2.72.7+2.7AP. The architecture search brings +2.22.2+2.2AP to the manually designed model. And the distillation brings +1.11.1+1.1AP to LitePose-XS.

references: As shown in Table 3 and Figure 7, with only minor computation increase, the 7×7777\times 7 kernels enhance the capability of coping with scale variation problem and therefore provides the best performance.

Another way to handle the scale variation problem is multi-resolution fusion as the introduction of large resolution features can help better capture small persons. We quantitatively show the performance gain in Table 3 and Figure 6: our efficient fusion deconv head improve the performance by +7.67.6+7.6AP on CrowdPose [26] dataset with only minor computation increase.

Neural Architecture Search (NAS) benefits our method from two aspects: one-shot supernet training and architecture search with fine-tuning. As shown in Table 3, supernet training provides +1.41.4+1.4AP and +2.72.7+2.7AP on 0.5 LitePose and LitePose-XS, respectively. Architecture search also offers +2.22.2+2.2AP on 0.5 LitePose. Besides, for LitePose-XS, we use LitePose-S as its teacher for heatmap loss in fine-tuning and obtain +1.11.1+1.1AP.
